frameDefinitions: An Entity is evaluated for whether or not it belongs to a particular Reference_category in a context where its category membership is doubtful.
An Agent acts in such a way as to give the incorrect impression to observers that a particular State_of_affairs holds.
This frame concerns an Evaluee being judged for its quality, i.e. how much it would probably be liked.

Against the background of a contextually salient non-real world, for instance a hypothetical, imagined, simulated, expected, projected, or dream world, an Instance of a Type encountered in a relation or event in the real world is presented as being different from the instance found in the non-real world.
The words in this frame describe the manipulation of an Entity by an Agent.
This frame concerns a specific subset of Instances of a Type which are evaluated in terms of their similarity to a conceptual prototype of the Type.
frameExamples:
It can be hard to get your money back after discovering you've bought a <t>bogus</t>
autograph for hundreds or thousands of dollars!
Jordan <t>feigned</t> a love of jazz music to get her phone number .
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Entity</fen> that is being evaluated in terms of whether it is an instance of the <fen>Reference_category</fen>.
The type relative to which the <fen>Entity</fen> is evaluated.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the person who acts in a misleading way to create the impression that a <fen>State_of_affairs</fen> holds.
This is the entity which is copied. With verbs it is frequently expressed as an NP Object: Pat <t>falsified</t> <fex name='Original'>the papers</fex>.
The Copy produced by the Creator most commonly occurs as the External Argument of a predicative use of an adjective or noun target: <fex name='Copy'>The painting</fex> is a <t>fake</t>.
The <fen>State_of_affairs</fen> is a an event, a state, or a property that the <fen>Agent</fen> wants others to believe have occurred or hold.
The place in which the <fen>Agent</fen> feigns something.
The <fen>Evaluee</fen> is being judged for its quality.
This role marks expressions that denote a scalar property of the <fen>Evaluee</fen> with respect to which the <fen>Evaluee</fen> is judged.
The real-world individual--a concrete or abstract thing or an event--which differs from its counterpart in a discourse-salient non-real world.
A kind of entity, instances of which are expected to occur in both the real and the non-real world.

The <fen>Agent</fen> manipulates an object. <fen>Agent</fen> typically refers to animate beings, but is also extended to mechanical and other inanimate objects.  <fen>Agent</fen> is most frequently expressed as the external argument of verbs:
The <fen>Entity</fen> being manipulated often occurs as the direct object of verbs:

The part of the <fen>Agent</fen>'s body being used to manipulate the <fen>Entity</fen> may also be expressed. While the default is for an <fen>Agent</fen> to use his/her hands, other body parts may be specified. This frame element usually occurs as a PP-complement.
The spatial setting in which the manipulation takes place.
A thing or episode that is considered exemplary of a certain <fen>Type</fen>.
The category of things or events from which an <fen>Instance</fen> is picked out.
listRoleExamples: <fex>The bomb found at the US Embassy in Berlin</fex> was fake.
A year after <fex>Audrey Seiler</fex> faked her own kidnapping while at college in Wisconsin, her lawyer says she's getting help and paying restitution.
A college student who staged <fex>her own disappearance</fex> last month will try to reach a plea agreement and avoid trial on charges she obstructed officers.
The Beaujolais Nouveau is dazzling <fex>in freshness</fex>.
In May of 1994, FBI agents working for Mr. Fiske interviewed Mrs. Foster, showed her <fex>an ACTUAL  gun</fex>, not a photo, and asked her if she could identify the gun.
<fex>A robot arm</fex> grasps the box on the conveyor belt and seals it.
Squeeze <fex>the ball</fex> as many times as you can.
Kim grasped the needle <fex>between finger and thumb</fex>.
I seized the letter <fex>before he did</fex>.
<fex>In the hallway</fex> he managed to grabthe monarch by the ankles
